Now, let us compute the standard deviation of Stock A by determining the square root of the variance that we have computed in the prior step. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Standard deviation}&= {\sqrt { 0.001809}}\\
&= {\textbf{4.25\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The standard deviation of Stock A is 4.25%.**

Now, let us compute the standard deviation of Stock B by determining the square root of the variance that we have computed in step 11. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Standard deviation}&= {\sqrt { 0.014904}}\\
&= {\textbf{12.21\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The standard deviation of Stock B is 12.21%.**
